I'm happy to talk more about that for all the runners here on the call.

00:03:44.039 --> 00:03:49.039
But that's usually if I'm not teaching a workshop, I'm usually doing some type of running.

00:03:50.479 --> 00:03:52.839
So I have a big schedule of running events this year.

00:03:52.839 --> 00:03:57.479
I have a few ultra marathons in Peru planned, and I'll be running in Chicago and in New York

00:03:57.479 --> 00:03:59.440
City marathons later this year.

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:05.279
I think running, just like the word running is a little bit of an understatement for you, Ryan.

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:08.119
Like an Uber runner.

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:10.080
What's the longest race you've ever run?

00:04:10.679 --> 00:04:11.960
I've run a few hundred milers.

00:04:12.639 --> 00:04:13.199
That's the longest.

00:04:13.199 --> 00:04:14.199
A few hundred milers.

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:15.399
I knew the answer to that question.

00:04:15.399 --> 00:04:24.119
I just wanted you to say it out loud because the walk to my mailbox and back, which is one third of a mile, is the most my heart can do.

00:04:24.119 --> 00:04:24.760
Let me tell you.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
OK, Marco says that's too far, Ryan.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:29.279
It's too far.

00:04:30.559 --> 00:04:31.880
And in a lot of ways, I would agree.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:33.279
Sometimes it is too far.

00:04:33.799 --> 00:04:40.920
I mean, I actually ran, I tried to run a hundred miler two weekends ago, but also came down with a stomach bug.

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:42.559
So I only got about 60 miles in.

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:47.239
So you are doing Boston and in New York this year, right?

00:04:47.679 --> 00:04:48.720
Chicago and New York.

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:50.000
Chicago, Chicago, New York.

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:52.440
OK, so Chicago, New York coming up.

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:59.040
We have, I ask because I know we have other marathon runners in the data science hangout community.

00:04:59.839 --> 00:05:02.160
Shout out to anybody who is prepping for a marathon.

00:05:02.519 --> 00:05:04.399
We love you and support you.

00:05:04.399 --> 00:05:06.040
And please send us pictures.

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:08.640
We can't wait to cheer for you.

00:05:09.399 --> 00:05:20.760
OK, so I have a lot of questions, but the first one that I would like to ask is, how did you get from a PhD in, is it microbiology?

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:23.839
Because you were like high throughput genetic data, right?

00:05:23.959 --> 00:05:26.399
How'd you get from there to industry?

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:31.880
Yeah, I think I just see Rachel posted the picture in the chat.

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:35.880
So last year, actually, Rachel and I ran the Boston Marathon.

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:38.119
That's a picture of us at the finish line.

00:05:39.799 --> 00:05:49.279
So, yeah, this topic, I actually think will resonate with a lot of folks here because I think it's been discussed in previous data science hangouts.

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:52.679
I wasn't always in the data science field.

00:05:53.519 --> 00:05:57.679
So I grew up in northeastern Pennsylvania.

00:05:58.279 --> 00:06:04.200
And then I went to college in a small liberal arts school called Juniata College.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:08.239
If folks are familiar with Penn State, it's right next to Penn State.

00:06:08.239 --> 00:06:09.799
It's about a 20 minute drive from Penn State.

00:06:10.559 --> 00:06:19.600
I have a very small school, about 1500 students total, where I got a degree in biology, just straight up biology, no specialty, just biology.

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:20.119
That's it.

00:06:21.079 --> 00:06:27.920
But definitely had a few good classes of microbiology, got into like a research lab while in undergrad.

00:06:28.239 --> 00:06:30.959
So I decided to get my Ph.D. in microbiology.

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:37.040
I went to I moved down to Maryland, which is actually where I lived before coming to Peru.

00:06:37.079 --> 00:06:40.079
So I've been living in Maryland for about like 15 years before that.

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:48.079
And I got a Ph.D. at a school that I would be very surprised if anybody has heard of.

00:06:48.079 --> 00:06:50.839
Actually, I saw someone in the chat mentioned like Wounded Warrior.

00:06:50.839 --> 00:06:51.920
So maybe you've heard of it.

00:06:52.359 --> 00:06:54.799
It's called the Uniformed Services University.

00:06:56.079 --> 00:06:58.760
It's actually OK, I see Derek with a little thumbs up there.

00:07:00.119 --> 00:07:04.239
If you're not familiar with it, you maybe have heard of Walter Reed Medical Hospital before.

00:07:04.959 --> 00:07:06.959
It's on the same base as Walter Reed.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:08.000
It's in the back.

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:16.480
And any a lot of times if you meet a medical doctor in the military, there's a good chance not, you know, 100 percent.

00:07:16.519 --> 00:07:20.640
But there's a good chance they probably got their medical training at Uniformed Services University.

00:07:21.359 --> 00:07:25.040
But in addition to MDs, they also have a Ph.D.

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:28.920
program, graduate school that's primarily civilians.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:30.160
And that's where I went.

00:07:30.480 --> 00:07:34.799
And the main draw was that they had a really good emerging infectious disease program.

00:07:34.839 --> 00:07:39.480
So, you know, things like Ebola, Nipah virus.

00:07:40.079 --> 00:07:43.799
Obviously, COVID was you know, I was graduated long before COVID.

00:07:43.799 --> 00:07:46.839
But that's the kind of stuff we were very interested in was a big draw for me.

00:07:48.119 --> 00:07:49.480
So when I started my Ph.D.

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:54.160
work, I was actually working on a bug that's not very emerging.

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:55.720
It's called Helicobacter pylori.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:07:57.880
It's a bug that lives in your gut.

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:00.640
H. pylori, I think a lot of people might know what that is.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:03.679
So some people may be familiar with that one.

00:08:03.679 --> 00:08:05.160
It actually infects a lot of people.

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:09.359
And oftentimes it's not a huge deal, but in some folks it can be.

00:08:09.679 --> 00:08:19.679
And when I was doing that type of research, I was very much like lab coat, pipette in hand, you know, at the bench doing your what you call wet bench science.

00:08:20.119 --> 00:08:22.119
I wasn't doing any data science at that point.

00:08:22.239 --> 00:08:26.640
I was just literally, you know, putting liquid from one beaker into another beaker.

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:27.799
That's literally what a Ph.D.

00:08:27.799 --> 00:08:28.600
program is.

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:39.039
But then I actually transitioned to a different project where it was much more I was actually doing microbiome work.

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:48.200
So I was studying all the bugs that primarily live in your nose, but also other crevices of your body and kind of how they interrelate with each other.

00:08:48.359 --> 00:08:50.640
And that came with a lot of high throughput sequencing.

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:57.400
So I've heard that kind of jargon term before you just send a sample off and you get a bunch of DNA sequencing back.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:05.679
But you typically need to analyze that sequencing somehow, which is actually how I got my first introduction to any type of data science.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:12.479
And at the time, there was a lot of great packages in R to do this type of work.

00:09:12.479 --> 00:09:16.479
So that's how I kind of found myself using R, got into R studio.

00:09:17.119 --> 00:09:25.200
And when I graduated, that was like my primary thesis work was that data science, high throughput sequencing, genomics data project.

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:31.520
So I finished that and then I literally jumped across the street.

00:09:31.559 --> 00:09:37.080
And for those that are familiar with Walter Reed, you'll know on the other side of the road is the National Institutes of Health.

00:09:37.159 --> 00:09:39.200
So it's all right there in Bethesda, Maryland.

00:09:39.799 --> 00:09:44.479
And I did a postdoc in a very similar field, high throughput sequencing.

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:47.559
I actually the project I was working on, I loved.

00:09:47.559 --> 00:09:54.119
It was really cool where we actually sampled a bunch of different water samples from the main clinical hospital.

00:09:54.200 --> 00:10:01.080
And we tried to track bugs as they circulated through the water system, which I thought was really it's kind of like being a detective.

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:04.119
But all using high throughput genomic sequencing data.

00:10:04.119 --> 00:10:08.719
So I kind of got a lot more training on data science, bioinformatics there.

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:19.200
I did not like my research advisor, though, she is a fantastic scientist, a very well-published scientist, but she was not a great mentor.

00:10:20.359 --> 00:10:23.640
And I just say that because she was mostly out of the office traveling.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:26.520
She gave us a lot of freedom to do whatever we wanted, which is great.

00:10:26.799 --> 00:10:31.479
But at the same time, gave me very little direction of where to go, very little help.

00:10:31.719 --> 00:10:34.960
So I relied a lot of other lab mates to help me out.

00:10:35.359 --> 00:10:37.640
You know, I was able to publish a few good papers.

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:42.039
I was very proud of. But that was kind of like my first indicator.

00:10:42.039 --> 00:10:46.239
I'm like, I didn't really enjoy this science as much as I thought I would.

00:10:46.239 --> 00:10:52.159
So about two years after that postdoc, I was like, I don't know if I want to do this anymore.

00:10:52.159 --> 00:10:55.799
So I went to my boss and I was like, I'm going to leave.

00:10:56.520 --> 00:10:59.359
And I'm going to become a staff scientist.

00:10:59.359 --> 00:11:10.640
And funny enough, I went back across the street again to the same school that I got my PhD work and started working as a staff scientist in basically a different lab doing a lot of the same stuff.

00:11:11.119 --> 00:11:15.760
This is also where I kind of got my first taste into more teaching.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:26.599
So while also doing some bioinformatics analysis, I was actually able to teach some bioinformatics courses, some machine learning courses at Uniform Services, which was really awesome.

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:33.599
But similarly, I told my new boss, I was like, hey, I'm happy to do the science.

00:11:33.599 --> 00:11:34.840
I'm happy to do the data science.

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:38.239
I love this stuff. I do not want to write grants.

00:11:38.239 --> 00:11:39.640
That is my one stipulation.

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:41.599
I really hate grant writing.

00:11:42.479 --> 00:11:48.760
For those that are not familiar with like the sciences, like a lot of times you have to get your own funding to fund your research.

00:11:49.679 --> 00:11:51.479
And I was just like, that's not what I want to do.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:58.559
So after about a year of doing the staff scientist, my boss comes into my office and is like, hey, would you mind writing a grant?

00:11:58.559 --> 00:12:01.280
And I'm like, that's not what I wanted to do.

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:04.719
So I did it for a little bit.

00:12:05.159 --> 00:12:07.080
Of course, I submitted it, didn't get funded.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:08.200
It's very demoralizing.

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:13.400
And I was just like, I don't think I like this as much as I thought I would.

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:23.679
So long story short, while doing the staff scientist position, this is actually my first time I got to go to a, at the time, our studio conference.

00:12:23.719 --> 00:12:26.599
It was when it was in Austin.

00:12:26.599 --> 00:12:30.359
So I think it was like 2019, 2019.

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:30.919
There we go.

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:32.799
So some of you folks may have been there as well.

00:12:33.559 --> 00:12:41.919
And during one of the social events at that conference, we went to Austin city limits where there was a really cool concert and I was just hanging out there.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:44.479
And a guy comes up to me and we just started chatting.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:47.559
Um, and funny enough, we were chatting about the Appalachian trail.

00:12:47.559 --> 00:12:52.200
So about a year before that, two years before that, I just finished hiking the Appalachian trail.

00:12:52.760 --> 00:12:56.119
And the guy I was speaking to was like, Hey, I really want to do the Appalachian trail.

00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:56.960
Let's chat.

00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:02.239
So we actually kind of like went off to the side and we just chatted all things, Appalachian trail for awhile.

00:13:02.799 --> 00:13:06.840
Turns out that guy was our VP of sales at positive, right?

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:08.719
Our studio at the time, his name was Jim Clemens.

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:09.640
He has since retired.

00:13:10.159 --> 00:13:13.719
And at the end of our conversation, he was just like, do you want a job?

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:20.479
And I was like, kind of, but I was still wanting to give this like staff scientist position a little bit more of a run.

00:13:20.479 --> 00:13:23.960
So I was like, not quite, but like, can I get your card?

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:28.880
I did the staff scientist position for about another, you know, seven, eight months.

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:31.960
And then I reached back out to Jim and I'm like, you know what, I think it's time.

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:37.159
Um, and this is when I made that really, really tough decision, which I know probably some folks here on the

00:13:37.159 --> 00:13:43.080
call may have had to make where I was in academia, I was writing research that I thought was like really

00:13:43.080 --> 00:13:45.000
impactful for like human health.

00:13:45.679 --> 00:13:47.280
And I had this degree, just PhD.

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:52.080
I spent my entire life in school for bioinformatics and I was about to leave that.

00:13:52.799 --> 00:13:55.320
And that was a very, very scary thing for me.

00:13:55.799 --> 00:14:01.159
Um, and I was at the time going to join customer success, which was like a field I knew nothing about.

00:14:01.159 --> 00:14:04.239
I mean, I knew data science, but I knew nothing about customer success.

00:14:04.239 --> 00:14:08.080
So this was like a really scary thing that me, my wife and I, we just had to like.

00:14:08.599 --> 00:14:10.840
Think about, talk about for a long time.

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:13.679
And ultimately it was probably the best decision I could have made.

00:14:14.039 --> 00:14:20.840
Um, so I started, I started at Posit, our studio in 2020 of March, March of 2020.

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:24.840
If some of you may know that date, because that's exactly the time COVID started.

00:14:25.479 --> 00:14:29.880
Um, fortunately, our studio is for the most part, a remote company.

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:35.559
So I was able to live in my basement for the next three years, worked out pretty well.

00:14:35.599 --> 00:14:41.559
Um, I was able to do my first like live event at our Posit conference when it was in DC and like

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:44.440
2022, I think, or 23, something like that.

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:50.520
And that's my long winded journey of how I came to be where I am today.

00:14:50.840 --> 00:14:54.039
Well, just in case you weren't looking at the chat, there were lots and lots of people

00:14:54.039 --> 00:14:58.559
identifying with not getting great mentorship in their PhD program or their postdocs.

00:14:59.119 --> 00:15:04.559
Um, it's an experience that is a little bit more pervasive than any of us would like it to be.

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:12.479
Um, but lots of, you know, also shared experiences around not wanting to write grants for a living.

00:15:12.479 --> 00:15:16.799
And that's the advice I got when I was trying to figure out whether I wanted to do a PhD.

00:15:16.799 --> 00:15:18.880
It was like, do you want to write grants for a living?

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:21.359
No, I don't want to do that at all.

00:15:22.239 --> 00:15:23.760
Maybe you shouldn't get a PhD.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.760
Well, this has been fantastic.

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:30.919
We have questions in the Slido that I think will launch us in great directions.

00:15:31.239 --> 00:15:33.320
I would love to start with Noor.

00:15:33.719 --> 00:15:38.119
Noor, you had a question in the chat, not in the chat, in the Slido, but I'm going to

00:15:38.119 --> 00:15:39.159
put it in the chat.

00:15:39.159 --> 00:15:40.119
That's what I was trying to say.

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:42.280
Would you like to ask that live?

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:47.159
Let's see, do we have her?

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:48.119
Hi.

00:15:48.119 --> 00:15:48.679
There she is.

00:15:48.679 --> 00:15:49.179
Hey.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:50.599
Hi, great to hear me.

00:15:50.599 --> 00:15:54.679
Hi, uh, fellow microbiome person or former microbiome person.

00:15:54.679 --> 00:15:57.559
My PhD was actually on the gut microbiome.

00:15:57.559 --> 00:16:03.080
So my postdoc was working on the lung microbiome, so almost microbiome.

00:16:03.080 --> 00:16:04.840
So I'm very familiar with the whole.

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:09.799
I'm also from Maryland, so I'm very familiar with like the whole Maryland biotech ecosystem

00:16:09.799 --> 00:16:13.080
that's currently slandered a lot at the moment.

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:13.799
But it's fine.

00:16:13.799 --> 00:16:14.359
It's fine.

00:16:14.359 --> 00:16:19.239
Anyway, question for someone who was formerly academia and is in industry.

00:16:19.239 --> 00:16:23.559
As someone who came from academia, what kind of skills do you find useful in industry versus

00:16:23.559 --> 00:16:27.159
what are some things you needed to learn, so to speak?

00:16:29.640 --> 00:16:33.400
Yeah, um, it's a good question.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:36.119
So maybe I'll kind of answer it in like both sides.

00:16:36.119 --> 00:16:40.599
Like, what did I find helpful for my PhD that I can still kind of keep going today?

00:16:41.239 --> 00:16:48.280
And also like, what have I learned today that, you know, maybe wasn't so prevalent in my

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:49.080
academia work?

00:16:49.559 --> 00:16:55.159
So for those that I have done a PhD or really kind of any type of, you know, more specialized

00:16:55.159 --> 00:17:02.679
education, there was a really good image I saw years ago of like what a PhD actually

00:17:02.679 --> 00:17:03.400
is.

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:09.560
So like when you go to, you know, high school and when you go to college, think of it as

00:17:09.560 --> 00:17:12.599
like your education just growing like a circle.

00:17:12.599 --> 00:17:17.160
Like you essentially are taking courses in a variety of fields and you're getting, you

00:17:17.160 --> 00:17:21.800
know, more well-rounded in a lot of different things, especially if you go to like a liberal

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:22.839
arts school like I did.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:29.800
When you go to then go to a PhD, think of that circle kind of, it stops growing for

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:34.920
the most part, but all of a sudden it gets like a random little bump in it, right?

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:37.800
That little bump in that circle is your PhD work.

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:43.880
You become so specialized in that one tiny little field that, and you learn a lot in

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:49.000
that little tiny field, but you kind of like, everything else kind of stays where it is.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:58.920
So like during my PhD work, if there's one thing that I still use today, which again,

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:00.839
I have no regrets of getting my PhD.

00:18:00.839 --> 00:18:05.479
Like I will never go back and say like I would never want to get a PhD after doing what I've

00:18:05.479 --> 00:18:09.800
done because a PhD is not necessarily like, oh, I have a PhD in microbiology and that's

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:11.640
the only thing I can do is microbiology.

00:18:11.719 --> 00:18:15.400
A PhD is all about like very critical thinking.

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:19.000
I obviously like the scientific method can apply to anything.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.800
It's not necessarily just to science.

00:18:21.800 --> 00:18:27.560
Like for example, in my work, when I'm designing like a workshop, like I don't just, just open

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:30.199
up PowerPoint and just start creating something.

00:18:30.199 --> 00:18:33.479
Like I go back, I collect as much data, as much research as I can.

00:18:33.479 --> 00:18:38.119
I form some type of hypothesis of like, what are people going to find the most value at?

00:18:38.119 --> 00:18:39.160
And then I test it out.

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:43.560
I talk around with some people, we do like some internal cohorts and it's going to get

00:18:43.560 --> 00:18:47.079
people's feedback until we ultimately create something that we think will deliver a lot

00:18:47.079 --> 00:18:48.119
of value.

00:18:48.119 --> 00:18:53.160
That's still something that I think from my PhD work that will stay with me, you know,

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:54.199
in my entire career.

00:18:54.199 --> 00:19:01.479
Something I had to learn in my, well, I also, the other thing I'll say as an academia, you

00:19:01.479 --> 00:19:02.520
present a lot.

00:19:02.520 --> 00:19:03.079
All right.

00:19:03.079 --> 00:19:04.359
So I was presenting a lot.

00:19:04.839 --> 00:19:08.760
I was also presenting at conferences, which seemed like every couple of months.

00:19:08.760 --> 00:19:13.479
And that's like a really good skill, especially for me that is presenting, you know, essentially

00:19:13.479 --> 00:19:17.880
every single day, public speaking is very, very good skill that I learned in PhD.

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:23.719
I will say though, the one thing that I learned, especially joining the customer success team

00:19:23.719 --> 00:19:30.040
that I did not have a lot of experience in was that I was a very, very good presenter.

00:19:30.040 --> 00:19:34.280
Something that I learned, especially joining the customer success team that I did not have

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:38.920
a lot of skills in is working with people and customers.

00:19:39.719 --> 00:19:44.760
Like a lot of times, like as a PhD, you're very kind of, I wouldn't say like self-centered,

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:49.000
that's not the right term, but like, you're just, you're very focused on your research

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.239
and advancing your research, getting published.

00:19:51.959 --> 00:19:56.119
And obviously you're trying to, you know, network and collaborate with others as well.

00:19:56.119 --> 00:20:00.920
But when you start to work in a industry field where people are buying your products,

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:06.439
like it's just a different animal and learning how to navigate that was a challenge,

00:20:06.439 --> 00:20:11.560
but something I was able to, you know, hopefully, you know, I have a better understanding now

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:13.479
because, you know, I still work at Posit.

