And for the first like two years as a data science advisor, this was probably one of the most, if not the most, popular workshops I was delivering.

00:35:25.393 --> 00:35:33.393
These were primarily, again, professional customers of Paws, but also some folks that just wanted to upskill on R and Python.

00:35:33.393 --> 00:35:43.393
Since the advent of AI, I have noticed a dramatic decline in the amount of teams that actually want to go through this workshop.

00:35:44.393 --> 00:35:48.393
I don't know if it's the primary reason or maybe I've just educated everybody at this point.

00:35:48.393 --> 00:35:58.393
But really, I'm finding that people have less of an appetite to essentially learn R from scratch when they can just ask AI like,

00:35:58.393 --> 00:36:05.393
hey, I want to create a shiny application that does X, Y, and Z and get something that's fairly usable and something they can iterate on pretty quickly.

00:36:06.393 --> 00:36:13.393
So because of that, I don't think I've delivered my intro to R, intro to Python workshop in like six months.

00:36:13.393 --> 00:36:17.393
So that's and I think that's directly attributed to AI.

00:36:17.393 --> 00:36:20.393
There could be other factors, but I really do think that's AI.

