00:46:39.393 --> 00:46:51.393
So, again, my focus, like for what I do on a day to day working with our professional customers, you know, these are folks, again, using either Posit Connect, Posit Workbench or Posit Package Manager.

00:46:51.393 --> 00:47:00.393
I would not have content to deliver if I couldn't teach like our open source tools being leveraged within our professional tools.

00:47:00.393 --> 00:47:01.393
That is what I do.

00:47:01.393 --> 00:47:05.393
Like when I deliver a workshop, it's usually like, hey, let's create a shiny application.

00:47:05.393 --> 00:47:09.393
And then I'm going to show you how to publish it to connect and share it with anybody you want.

00:47:09.393 --> 00:47:12.393
That is a very typical workshop that I deliver.

00:47:12.393 --> 00:47:18.393
So all of our professional tools 100% rely on open source tools.

00:47:18.393 --> 00:47:21.393
And that's kind of like our business model really at Posit.

00:47:21.393 --> 00:47:25.393
Like we have so many engineering folks here at Posit.

00:47:25.393 --> 00:47:29.393
And I can never remember like the actual statistic because it's constantly changing.

00:47:29.393 --> 00:47:35.393
But we used to say something like over half of our engineers at Posit work purely on open source.

00:47:35.393 --> 00:47:47.393
So, of course, we at Posit, we certainly hope open source continues to go, go, go and grow bigger and bigger over time.

00:47:47.393 --> 00:47:54.393
Now, as kind of being alluded to a little bit, like, you know, open source is a little bit of a double edged sword.

00:47:54.393 --> 00:48:01.393
Like you always get bleeding edge data science tools that can really help grow your data science projects.

00:48:01.393 --> 00:48:05.393
But at the same time, like there is certainly, you know, for production work,

00:48:05.393 --> 00:48:11.393
a little bit of a concern that like anybody can create a open source R Python package

00:48:11.393 --> 00:48:19.393
and they could implement some malicious code or they could pull the plug from that package and stop implementing it.

00:48:19.393 --> 00:48:21.393
So there's a little bit of a concern there as well.

00:48:21.393 --> 00:48:26.393
But I will just say like that's what our professional tools do for a lot of our customers.

00:48:26.393 --> 00:48:33.393
It just gives them a little bit more structure and a little bit more security for using open source tools,

00:48:33.393 --> 00:48:37.393
particularly within package manager or sorry for Workbench and Connect.

